(1548, 222, 'blog-page_post-title', 'Overcoming Client Barriers with SEO Testing'),
(1549, 222, '_blog-page_post-title', 'field_624037cce57a5'),
(1550, 222, 'blog-page_post-title-2', 'Why SEO Split-Testing? 2'),
(1551, 222, '_blog-page_post-title-2', 'field_6240387b593c1'),
(1552, 222, 'blog-page_post-title-3', '6 Best Practices for Split-Testing Your SEO Recommendations 3'),
(1553, 222, '_blog-page_post-title-3', 'field_624038a578006'),
(1554, 222, 'blog-page_post-title-4', '6 Best Practices for Split-Testing Your SEO Recommendations 4'),
(1555, 222, '_blog-page_post-title-4', 'field_624038b5edaab'),
(1556, 222, 'blog-page_post-title-5', '6 Best Practices for Split-Testing Your SEO Recommendations 5'),
(1557, 222, '_blog-page_post-title-5', 'field_62403a7cc0fca'),
(1558, 222, 'blog-page_post-title-6', '6 Best Practices for Split-Testing Your SEO Recommendations 6'),
(1559, 222, '_blog-page_post-title-6', 'field_624038da04ef2'),
(1560, 222, 'blog-page_post-text', 'As someone who works in the space, I have seen many custom solutions developed from agency to agency over the years to tackle problems like the above. And, in talking to agency owners and SEOs, I can tell you it used to be much harder to do any kind of split-testing before the advent of SEO SaaS split-testing tools, like <a href=\"#\" class=\"blog-page-post__article-list--link\">SplitSignal</a>.\r\n\r\nNow, however, it’s as simple as coming up with a testable idea (your hypothesis), setting up a line of JavaScript on your client’s website (via Google Tag Manager, something similar, or just drop the line directly into the head of the website code), set up a split test in the tool to measure your hypothesis.<br>\r\n\r\nRead more about SEO split-testing: <a class=\"blog-page-post__article-list--link post__category\" href=\"#\">SEO A/B Split Testing 101</a> '),
(1561, 222, '_blog-page_post-text', 'field_62403c655057b'),
(1562, 222, 'blog-page_post-text-2', 'Running measurable tests on statistically significant quantities of traffic to your website can break down the barriers to having your recommendations implemented quickly and rapidly demonstrate the value of you as an individual or your agency as a whole.\r\n\r\nWhether you have a positive or negative test, you can show value. A positive test can be prioritized for implementation based on the overall impact it’s going to have on the website. A 50% increase in traffic, for example, should be a pretty high priority for your client (and you). A negative test result isn’t a bad thing; it keeps you from wasting precious time and budget on implementing something that isn’t going to work. As you know, what works in one vertical doesn’t always work in another.'),
(1563, 222, '_blog-page_post-text-2', 'field_62403e1a4d44a'),
(1564, 222, 'blog-page_post-text-start', 'When you’re working with clients who expect a return on investment from their SEO budget (as most clients do and should), it often presents several challenges for the SEO practitioner:'),
(1565, 222, '_blog-page_post-text-start', 'field_62403abc62114'),
(1566, 222, 'blog-page_post-list-item', 'How do you cost-justify your SEO recommendation without being able to prove its value (beyond, “we’ve seen this work before”)?'),
(1567, 222, '_blog-page_post-list-item', 'field_62403d0a89b80'),
(1568, 222, 'blog-page_post-list-item-2', 'How do you cost-justify your SEO recommendation without being able to prove its value (beyond, “we’ve seen this work before”)?'),
(1569, 222, '_blog-page_post-list-item-2', 'field_62403d3239187'),
(1570, 222, 'blog-page_post-list-item-3', 'How do you cost-justify your SEO recommendation without being able to prove its value (beyond, “we’ve seen this work before”)?'),
(1571, 222, '_blog-page_post-list-item-3', 'field_62403d8dc075a'),
(1572, 222, 'blog-page_post-list-item-4', 'How do you cost-justify your SEO recommendation without being able to prove its value (beyond, “we’ve seen this work before”)?'),
(1573, 222, '_blog-page_post-list-item-4', 'field_62403d9bc075b'),
(1574, 222, 'blog-page_post-text-3', 'Once your testing tool is ready to go, you need a test you can configure and run. Developing a <a class=\"blog-page-post__article-list--link post__category\" href=\"#\">hypothesis</a> is simply asking a question. For example, will adding “Holidays 2021” (or your current year if you’re reading this in the future!) to your meta title <a class=\"blog-page-post__article-list--link post__category\" href=\"#\">improve the click-through rate to your products during the holiday season</a>?\r\n\r\nBy choosing high-impact elements within your website (e.g., title tags, heading elements, meta descriptions, etc.), you can draft simple tests with significant rewards. However, if your test is too narrow, you may not be able to observe enough of an impact to draw any helpful conclusions.'),
(1575, 222, '_blog-page_post-text-3', 'field_62403eb4353cd'),
(1576, 222, 'blog-page_post-text-4', 'Once your testing tool is ready to go, you need a test you can configure and run. Developing a <a class=\"blog-page-post__article-list--link post__category\" href=\"#\">hypothesis</a> is simply asking a question. For example, will adding “Holidays 2021” (or your current year if you’re reading this in the future!) to your meta title <a class=\"blog-page-post__article-list--link post__category\" href=\"#\">improve the click-through rate to your products during the holiday season</a>?\r\n\r\nBy choosing high-impact elements within your website (e.g., title tags, heading elements, meta descriptions, etc.), you can draft simple tests with significant rewards. However, if your test is too narrow, you may not be able to observe enough of an impact to draw any helpful conclusions.\r\n\r\nOnce you have your hypothesis at hand, you’ll be ready to start implementing your test because what you want to test should be clearly defined.\r\n'),
